##
# Liferay Docker Scripts - Example Hosts File
#
# This file demonstrates how to map multiple Liferay instances to unique 
# loopback addresses. This allows you to run multiple portals on port 8080 
# and multiple Elasticsearch sidecars on port 9200 without collisions.
##

# Standard Loopback
127.0.0.1       localhost
::1             localhost
255.255.255.255 broadcasthost

# Instance 1 - primary.liferay.local
# Usage: ./liferay-docker.sh run --host-name primary.liferay.local -p 8080
127.0.0.1       primary.liferay.local

# Instance 2 - secondary.liferay.local
# Usage: ./liferay-docker.sh run --host-name secondary.liferay.local -p 8080
127.0.0.2       secondary.liferay.local

# Instance 3 - development.liferay.local (Custom IP)
# Usage: ./liferay-docker.sh run --host-name development.liferay.local -p 8080
127.0.0.74      development.liferay.local

# --- macOS NOTE ---
# On macOS, if you use a loopback IP other than 127.0.0.1, you must also alias it:
# sudo ifconfig lo0 alias 127.0.0.74 up
# ------------------

# Infrastructure
127.0.0.1       kubernetes.docker.internal
